{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":128,"record_hash":"sha256:60233f78a6ad215761689dff55b500e86c041bd1c0c94e9374c304b6c7cb710c","timestamp":"2026-05-20T00:58:28.465Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 10c685\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2957\nOutput:\n     1\t# Including Turns In Agentlog\n     2\t\n     3\tThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of an\n     4\tagent session turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\n     5\trecords.\n     6\t\n     7\tThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n     8\t[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\n     9\tcautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\n    10\tas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\n    11\tunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n    12\t\n    13\tToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n    14\t\n    15\t```text\n    16\tproject session -> transcript records\n    17\t```\n    18\t\n    19\tThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\n    20\tto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\n    21\tthat moment. A turn layer would preserve that missing context without forcing us\n    22\tto immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit, change, or\n    23\tpull request.\n    24\t\n    25\t## Product Use Cases\n    26\t\n    27\tKeep this grounded in the same two use cases as the rest of the agent-session\n    28\tcapture project.\n    29\t\n    30\t### 1. Session Handoff\n    31\t\n    32\tHandoff wants enough project-scoped session context to continue work on another\n    33\tmachine or with another agent. For this use case, turns help because they add\n    34\tstructure:\n    35\t\n    36\t- the session can be reconstructed as a sequence of user/agent interactions\n    37\t- a future reader can see the repository state around each interaction\n    38\t- consumers can choose the latest turn, a specific turn, or a window of turns\n    39\t  instead of treating the whole transcript as one flat blob\n    40\t\n    41\n[TRUNCATED]\n same repository metadata access boundary as the\n   209\tcode. Do not store absolute paths. Re-check this assumption before exposing the\n   210\tsame metadata in product surfaces with a narrower audience than repository\n   211\taccess, such as selected web review links.\n   212\t\n   213\tFor file paths, store relative paths plainly on the turn snapshot. They are\n   214\timportant evidence and keep explanations understandable. The normal case should\n   215\tnot be expensive. Guard only against pathological cases such as mass renames,\n   216\tgenerated trees, vendor drops, or giant lockfile-driven commits by storing a\n   217\tcount and truncated flag alongside a capped sorted path list.\n   218\t\n   219\tExample shape:\n   220\t\n   221\t```json\n   222\t{\n   223\t  \"worktree_files\": [\"src/foo.rs\", \"src/bar.rs\"],\n   224\t  \"worktree_file_count\": 2,\n   225\t  \"worktree_files_truncated\": false\n   226\t}\n   227\t```\n   228\t\n   229\tCommit file lists should use the same pattern:\n   230\t\n   231\t```json\n   232\t{\n   233\t  \"files\": [\"src/foo.rs\", \"Cargo.toml\"],\n   234\t  \"file_count\": 2,\n   235\t  \"files_truncated\": false\n   236\t}\n   237\t```\n   238\t\n   239\tIf a list exceeds the cap, store the first capped set in deterministic sorted\n   240\torder plus the total count and `*_truncated = true`. Path hashes can be added\n   241\tlater if matching beyond the cap becomes necessary, but they should not be part\n   242\tof the first shape.\n   243\t\n   244\t## Association Signals\n   245\t\n   246\tTurns make association a layered evidence problem rather than a single\n   247\tcapture-time guess.\n   248\t\n   249\t### Signal 1: Observed Branch Counts\n   250\t\n   251\tAcross all turns in a session, count which branches or stack branches were\n   252\tobserved while the user was working.\n   253\t\n   254\tExample:\n   255\t\n   256\t- `main` observed a few times\n   257\t- `my-feature` observed many more times\n   258\t\n   259\tThat may indicate the user started prompting while still on `main`, then moved\n   260\tto `my-feature`. This is useful, but weak on its own because a GitButler\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T00:58:28.465Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}